Cars4U Project¶

by Michele Casalgrandi

Background¶

Cars4U is a tech start-up that operates in the Indian used cars market.

One of Cars4U aims is to be able to accurately predict cars market value to assist in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing.

Objective¶

  1. Explore and visualize data set
  2. Build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars
  3. Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help with the business

Data Dictionary¶

S.No. : Serial Number
Name : Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name
Location : The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase Cities
Year : Manufacturing year of the car
Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM.
Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car. (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car. (Automatic / Manual)
Owner_Type : Type of ownership
Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC.
Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp.
Seats : The number of seats in the car.
New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs.(1 Lakh = 100, 000)
Price : The price of the used car in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh = 100, 000)

In [155]:
# function to extract the units of measure (trailing word)
def get_unit_of_measure(value):
    ''' 
    Return trailing unit of measure.  
    Expects the number and unit of measure to be separated by a space
    '''
    if isinstance(value, str):
        return value.split(" ")[1]
    else:
        return np.nan

# extract the units of measure from the columns
for column in object_to_num_columns:
    units_of_measure = cars[column].apply(get_unit_of_measure)
    print(f'\n {column} units of measure: {units_of_measure.unique()}')

 Mileage units of measure: ['km/kg' 'kmpl' nan]

 Power units of measure: ['bhp']

 Engine units of measure: ['CC']

'Power' and 'Engine' have a single unit of measure.

For 'Mileage' even though 'kmpl' and 'km/kg' are not directly comparable, we will rely on the column 'Fuel_Type' in the model to help compensate for the difference in weight that unit of measure should have.

We will remove the units of measure so the columns can be converted to numeric and be used in the model.

In [156]:
# define function to remove the trailing part of a string after the first space
def get_first_word(value, separator=" "):
    ''' 
    Return first word delimited by separator from a string value.  
    '''
    if isinstance(value, str):
        return value.split(separator)[0]
    else:
        return np.nan

# remove units of measure for the applicable columns
for column in object_to_num_columns:
    cars[column] = cars[column].apply(get_first_word)

# define function to plot histogram and boxplot for a feature
# taken from Anime rating case study
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15, 10), bins=None):
    """Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (15,10))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        feature.mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        feature.median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Distributions¶
  • 'S.No.' has uniform distribution
  • 'Year' is skewed to the left with most values between 2009 and 2018
  • _'KilometersDriven' is highly skewed to the right with one or more extreme outliers
  • 'Mileage' has a close to normal distribution with a number of outliers grouped at zero
  • 'Engine' has a multimodal distribution with many values between 1000 and 2000. It is also skewed to the right with some outliers
  • Seats is not a continuous variable and although it is numeric, we will change to be a categorical type
  • Price is highly skewed to the right with two or more extreme outliers
  • 'Power' is highly skewed to the right

We will review each variable.

Numerical variables scaling.¶

Because some numerical variables have different orders of magnitudes (fro example, 'Mileage' is typically two orders of magnitude lower than 'Engine'), it would be difficult to interpret the importance a certain feature has based on the coefficients of unscaled variables.

We will use a MinMax scaler to scale variables in the range 0 to 1 (default).

In [216]:
# function to extract trailing part of string after separator
def get_trailing_words(value, separator=" "):
    '''Return trailing part of string after first occurence of separator'''
    if isinstance(value, str):
        if separator in value:
            return ''.join(value.split(separator, maxsplit=1)[1:])
        else:
            return value
    else:
        return np.nan
In [217]:

    'Model': get_trailing_words
}

    cars_eda[col] = cars_eda['Name'].map(func)

# Function to plot categories as percent of total
def perc_on_bar(data, z):
    """
    plot categorical var data[z] in bars with percentages
    """
    total = len(data[z])  # length of the column
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    ax = sns.countplot(data[z], palette="Paired")
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = "{:.1f}%".format(
            100 * p.get_height() / total
        )  # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()  # hieght of the plot

        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size=10)  # annotate the percantage
    plt.show()  # show the plot

def encode_cat_vars(x_vars):
    ''' Return a dataframe with all columns of type object and category converted to dummy variables '''
    x = pd.get_dummies(
        x_vars,
        columns=x_vars.select_dtypes(include=["object", "category"]).columns.tolist(),
        drop_first=True
    )
    return x

Coefficients Interpretation¶

  • Year (18), Engine (33) and Power_log (19) have large positive coefficients. An increase in year (lower age) , engine size, and power will result in a higher price.

  • Location: most locations have positive coefficients, while some are negative. As they are hot encoded this means prices will differ based on location.

  • Seats: all seats coefficient are negative, reflecting the fact the cars with two seats (baseline) are more expensive. Seats coefficient vary between approx. -13 (4 seats) and -18 (10 seats).
    Although they have high absolute values, the coefficients for seats are significant only in relationship to the baseline.

  • Make: all make coefficients, with the exception of Mercedes-Benz, are negative. Meaning most cars are less expensive than the baseline (Audi). Coefficients vary between -11.5 (Mahindra) and 0.90 (Mercedes-Benz). 'Other' coefficient is -5.2.

  • The fuel type 'Electric' is high, signifying 'Electric' models have higher prices. Note: there are only two electric cars in the dataset.

  • Higher kilometers driven and higher 'Mileage' will tend to lower the price.

Check Model Performance¶

In [258]:
# Define functions for metrics
# Taken from AnimeRating case study

# Adjusted R^2
def adj_r2(ind_vars, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = ind_vars.shape[0]
    k = ind_vars.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# Model performance check
def model_perf(model, inp, out):

    y_pred = model.predict(inp)
    y_act = out.values

    return pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_act, y_pred)),
            "MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_act, y_pred),
            "R^2": r2_score(y_act, y_pred),
            "Adj. R^2": adj_r2(inp, y_act, y_pred),
        },
        index=[0],
    )

  • The train and test $R^2$ are $0.736$ and $0.718$. The model explains ~74% of the variability in price. The scores are comparable.
    The $Adj R^2$ are $0.733$ and $0.711$, slightly lower than $R^2$ but comparable.
    The model does not seem to be overfit.
  • $RMSE$ is about the same for train and test.
  • $MAE$ is around $3.4$ for test and $3.53$ for train.
  • The overall performance is acceptable.
  • While fitting the model, it was noticed that it is sensitive to how the data is split between train and test (see below)
Fit linear regression models with different random seeds and split sizes for train and test.¶
In [260]:
# define a function to split data, fit a linear regression and return a df with performance metrics
def fit_linear_regression(x, y, test_split, random_seed):
    # split the datasets
    x_trn, x_tst, y_trn, y_tst = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=test_split, random_state=random_seed)
    # train
    train_hpar = pd.DataFrame({"Split": test_split, "Seed": random_seed, "Set": 'TRAIN'}, index=[0])
    res_df = pd.concat([model_perf(linr_model, x_trn, y_trn), train_hpar], axis=1)
    # test
    test_hpar = pd.DataFrame({"Split": test_split, "Seed": random_seed, "Set": 'Test'}, index=[0])
    res_df = res_df.append(pd.concat([model_perf(linr_model, x_tst, y_tst), test_hpar], axis=1))

    return res_df

Conclusions¶

  • A predictive model was built to predict cars prices with an $Adj. R^2$ of $0.718$ on the test set.

  • The model can be used to predict cars prices with a mean absolute error of $3.53$ on the test set.

  • The year of the car, the power and engine size are factors which tend to increase the price.
    Note that engine size and power are strongly correlated (0.86).

  • Mileage and Km_log (log of 'Kilometers_Driven') will lower the price of a car as they increase.

  • For the purpose of differential pricing, it was found that Location is a factor that influences price, and suggests that price for the same car could be adjusted based on location, as customers might we willing to pay higher prices in certain locations.
    E.g. Coimbatore, Hyderabad and Bangalore have price differentials of +1.7 to +2.2 as compared to the baseline location (Ahmedabad).

  • Engine size (displacement) and power also have large coefficients, suggesting that customers are sensitive to those specifications. E.g. cars with high power and engine displacement could be priced higher.

  • Because of the high number of different car models, that feature (derived from 'Name') was not used in training the linear model. It is probable that it has a high predictive power for price. Other non-linear models that can deal with high number of categorical values should be considered, as they might be more effective in predicting price.
